&lt;p&gt;TOKYO&amp;mdash;After soaring over the previous two weeks, shares in Nintendo Co. plunged Monday following a company warning that the smash-hit smartphone game &amp;ldquo;Pok&amp;eacute;mon Go&amp;rdquo; would make a limited contribution to its earnings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nintendo &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/7974?countrycode=jp&quot;&gt;7974, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-17.72%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; shares were down 17.7% to &amp;yen;23,370 ($219.88) in afternoon trading. The company&amp;rsquo;s share price had doubled since Pok&amp;eacute;mon Go was released in the U.S. and other markets this month.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Shares of McDonald&amp;rsquo;s Corp.&amp;rsquo;s Japan unit &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/2702?countrycode=jp&quot;&gt;2702, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-11.60%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp;, which announced a &amp;ldquo;Pok&amp;eacute;mon Go&amp;rdquo; tie-up last week, also reversed direction Monday, tumbling 11.8 to &amp;yen;3,250.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Based on a Nintendo franchise, Pok&amp;eacute;mon Go is the Japanese videogame maker&amp;rsquo;s first mobile-gaming hit. But it was developed by Tokyo-based Pok&amp;eacute;mon Co., in which Nintendo owns a 32% stake, and San Francisco-based Niantic Inc., in which Pok&amp;eacute;mon Co. owns an undisclosed stake.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/on-pokemon-go-why-so-many-people-are-choosing-team-mystic-2016-07-13&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;On Pokemon Go, why so many people are choosing team Mystic&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kyoto-based Nintendo said after the market closed Friday that it had already factored in any profits from sales of its &amp;ldquo;Pok&amp;eacute;mon Go Plus&amp;rdquo; wearable device into its current forecast of &amp;yen;35 billion for the fiscal year ending in March.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The company is scheduled to report its April-June results Wednesday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/nintendo-shares-take-hit-from-notice-on-pokemon-go-earnings-1469424667&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An extended version of this story can be found at WSJ.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The best-paid CEOs tend to run some of the worst-performing companies and vice versa&amp;mdash;even when pay and performance are measured over the course of many years, according to a new study.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The analysis, from corporate-governance research firm MSCI, examined the pay of some 800 CEOs at 429 large and midsize U.S. companies during the decade ending in 2014, and also looked at the total shareholder return of the companies during the same period.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;MSCI found that $100 invested in the 20% of companies with the highest-paid CEOs would have grown to $265 over 10 years. The same amount invested in the companies with the lowest-paid CEOs would have grown to $367. The report is expected to be released as early as Monday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The results call into question a fundamental tenet of modern CEO pay: the idea that significant slugs of stock options or restricted stock, especially when the size of the award is also tied to company performance in other ways, helps drive better company performance, which in turn will improve results for shareholders. Equity incentive awards now make up 70% of CEO pay in the U.S.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The highest paid had the worst performance by a significant margin,&amp;rdquo; said Ric Marshall, a senior corporate governance researcher at MSCI. &amp;ldquo;It just argues for the equity portion of CEO pay to be more conservative.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/best-paid-ceos-run-some-of-worst-performing-companies-1469419262&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An extended version of this story can be found at WSJ.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Crude oil prices fell in early Monday trade in Asia as the prospect of more oil-digging activities in the U.S. and a growing glut of distillate fuel pessimism that the oil market is tightening at a slower pace than previously expected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On the New York Mercantile Exchange, light, sweet crude futures for delivery in September &lt;span class=&quot;quote unchanged bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/future/clu6&quot;&gt;CLU6, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.00%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; traded at $44.16 a barrel, down $0.02 in the Globex electronic session. September Brent crude &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/future/lcou6?countrycode=uk&quot;&gt;LCOU6, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.02%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp;London&amp;rsquo;s ICE Futures exchange fell $0.03 to $45.66 a barrel. Oil prices have been under the $50-a-barrel threshold for weeks thanks to multiple bearish factors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Britain&amp;rsquo;s decision in June to leave the European Union left market players wondering about the possible contagion effects on regional economic health and oil demand.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The steady growth in the number of active oil rigs digging for oil in the U.S. is spurring concerns of more shale output in the future. Moreover, the ballooning glut of distillates, such as gasoline and diesel, around the world is darkening the outlook.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On Friday, industry group Baker Hughes reported that the U.S. oil rig count climbed by 14 to 371, marking a fourth straight weekly increase. The rise was mostly buoyed by the recent price rally as prices went from around $25 a barrel in February to the current level.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/largest-us-oil-rig-spike-of-2016-is-bad-for-prices-good-for-oil-service-firms-2016-07-22&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Largest U.S. oil-rig spike of 2016 is bad for prices, good for oil-service firms&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The uptrend in the rig count can be thought as a rebalancing of the rebalancing that may slow the rate of decline in U.S. crude production,&amp;rdquo; said Tim Evans, an energy analyst at Citi Futures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;U.S. gasoline stocks grew 900,000 barrels last week while China&amp;rsquo;s exports of gasoline in June surged to a historical high.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;[The growth in distillate] was to be expected as many refiners were producing in a full swing while we are coming to the end of the driving season,&amp;rdquo; said Avtar Sandhu, Asian commodities analysts at Phillip Futures, who tips prices could test support at around the $41 level.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Multiple supply disruptions around the world are also coming to an end. In Nigeria, police arrested a key militant responsible for attacks on oil infrastructure, according to an AFP report.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In addition to weekly oil inventories data from the U.S. energy department on Wednesday, investors this week will be keeping a close eye on two major central banks &amp;mdash; the Bank of Japan and the U.S. Federal Reserve &amp;mdash; for their decisions on interest rates and outlooks on their respective countries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The U.S. Federal Open Market Committee will meet on July 26 to 27, followed by the Bank of Japan&amp;rsquo;s policy meeting on July 28 to 29.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nymex reformulated gasoline blendstock for August &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/future/rbq6&quot;&gt;RBQ6, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-0.40%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp;&amp;mdash; the benchmark gasoline contract--fell 29 points to $1.3586 a gallon, while August diesel traded at $1.3603, 33 points higher.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ICE gasoil for August changed hands at $398.75 a metric ton, up $3.50 from Friday&amp;rsquo;s settlement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Salesforce.com Inc. Chief Executive Marc Benioff, who lost a bidding war for LinkedIn Corp. to Microsoft Corp., told the social networking company that he would have made a stronger bid had it continued talks with him after its call for final offers. The information appeared Friday in a LinkedIn regulatory filing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Microsoft Corp. &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/msft&quot;&gt;MSFT, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+1.38%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; on&amp;nbsp;June 13&amp;nbsp;said it would acquire LinkedIn &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/lnkd&quot;&gt;LNKD, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.20%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; for $26.2 billion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;According to the filing, the CEO of &amp;ldquo;Party A&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; previously identified by The Wall Street Journal as Salesforce &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/crm&quot;&gt;CRM, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+1.04%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp;&amp;mdash; sent an email to LinkedIn CEO Jeff Weiner and LinkedIn Chairman Reid Hoffman after reading a July 1 regulatory filing that detailed events leading up to LinkedIn&amp;rsquo;s May 12 call to the two bidders for &amp;ldquo;best and final offers,&amp;rdquo; and its subsequent agreement to negotiate exclusively with Microsoft.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Benioff&amp;rsquo;s email said he would have offered a &amp;ldquo;much higher&amp;rdquo; price and a different mix of cash and stock had LinkedIn continued to communicate with his company.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;LinkedIn said in the filing that it received its last offer from Salesforce on&amp;nbsp;June 5, after it had signed the exclusivity agreement. The social networking company noted that the bid didn&amp;rsquo;t include a higher price or a different mix of cash and stock than Salesforce had offered previously. LinkedIn&amp;rsquo;s Transactions Committee reviewed the situation and decided not to respond, according to the filing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/salesforce-would-have-bid-much-higher-for-linkedin-1469417209&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stock markets across Asia were mostly higher&amp;nbsp;Monday, though weakness in commodities-related shares dragged in Hong Kong.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Australia&amp;rsquo;s S&amp;amp;P ASX 200 &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/xjo?countrycode=au&quot;&gt;XJO, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.54%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; was up 0.7%, Japan&amp;rsquo;s Nikkei Stock Average &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/nik?countrycode=jp&quot;&gt;NIK, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.38%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; edged up 0.4% and the Shanghai Composite Index &lt;span class=&quot;quote up bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/shcomp?countrycode=cn&quot;&gt;SHCOMP, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.24%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; inched up 0.2%. The Hang Seng Index &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/hsi?countrycode=hk&quot;&gt;HSI, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-0.19%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; was off 0.1% while South Korea&amp;rsquo;s Kospi &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/seu?countrycode=kr&quot;&gt;SEU, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-0.09%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; slipped 0.1%.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Expectations for easing from global central banks have kept most Asian markets moving higher, as has a rebound in flows to emerging markets in recent months. The Hong Kong market was stepping back after entering bull-market territory last week, a more than 20% rise from a recent low.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During the week of July 14-20, investors bought up to $9.1 billion of Asian equities, the biggest weekly flow since 2014, according to Jefferies. Flows went into Japan, where foreign investors have been hoping for &amp;ldquo;helicopter money&amp;rdquo; from the government &amp;mdash; a direct cash injection into the economy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This week, investors are hoping for a big stimulus announcement from the Bank of Japan, which meets for a two-day policy meeting&amp;nbsp;Thursday. Officials have signaled a reluctance to act, although expectations are rising that they will. Meanwhile, the U.S. Federal Reserve isn&amp;rsquo;t expected to raise interest rates when it meets&amp;nbsp;Wednesday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Still, &amp;ldquo;there&amp;rsquo;s not a huge positive catalyst right this second,&amp;rdquo; said Ilya Feygin, managing director of WallachBeth Capital.&amp;nbsp;Feygin said that action from the Bank of Japan&amp;nbsp;this Friday&amp;nbsp;could disappoint the market.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In Hong Kong, the market&amp;rsquo;s decline Monday morning was led by materials and energy shares, which were off 0.8% and 0.6% respectively. Shares of Hong Kong-listed Sinopec Engineering Group Co. &lt;span class=&quot;quote down bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/2386?countrycode=hk&quot;&gt;2386, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;-5.14%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; slumped 4.3% after the firm issued a profit warning&amp;nbsp;for its first-half results. The unit of Chinese oil refining giant Sinopec said the global economic slowdown and low oil prices are hurting business.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Trading in Hong Kong will also be extended by a few minutes starting Monday, as the Hong Kong Exchanges &amp;amp; Clearing tests its first phase of a closing auction in its securities market. Most developed markets have such auctions to determine final trading prices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When such a measure was tested in 2008, there was a sharp drop in HSBC Holding PLC &lt;span class=&quot;quote unchanged bgQuote&quot;&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;qt-chip trackable&quot; href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/0005?countrycode=hk&quot;&gt;0005, &lt;span class=&quot;bgPercentChange&quot;&gt;+0.00%&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;nbsp; shares. HKEx says it has introduced a volatility control mechanism to deal with sharp volatility in closing prices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;TOKYO &amp;mdash; Japanese exports fell for a ninth straight month in June, highlighting how manufacturers have been struggling with rises in the yen that accelerated toward the end of the month following a U.K. vote to leave the European Union.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Merchandise exports decreased 7.4% from a year earlier to Y6.026 trillion ($56.8 billion) last month, after an 11.3% drop the previous month, according to data released Monday by the finance ministry. Economists surveyed by The Wall Street Journal had also expected an 11.3% decrease in June.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Investors have grown more doubtful over Japan&amp;rsquo;s economic prospects since the result of the U.K. referendum on June 23 sent the yen higher, briefly pushing the currency beyond Y100 to the dollar, although it has fallen back recently. The yen&amp;rsquo;s appreciation this year has made Japan-made products less competitive abroad at a time of slowing global growth. It has also reduced manufacturers&amp;rsquo; repatriated profits.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Exports to the U.S., the largest destination for Japanese shipments, fell 6.5% in June, down for a fourth straight month, according to the ministry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An expanded version of this report appears on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;WSJ.com&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A pedestrian ramp to a subway station in Chicago collapsed Sunday during a heavy storm after it was apparently hit by lightning. Officials said no one was injured.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The collapse was captured on video, and came during a severe thunderstorm that brought 60-mph winds, hail and torrential rain that left more than 30,000 people without power.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;inset external-content-inset&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot;&gt;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Just passed the L collapsing at Racine on 290- unbelievable! &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/hashtag/storms?src=hash&quot;&gt;#storms&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/BenBradleyABC7&quot;&gt;@BenBradleyABC7&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/jerrytaft&quot;&gt;@jerrytaft&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.co/nC2tXuUXqo&quot;&gt;pic.twitter.com/nC2tXuUXqo&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&amp;mdash; Isles OfErin (@IslesofErin) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/IslesofErin/status/757364207859986432&quot;&gt;July 24, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;inset external-content-inset&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot;&gt;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Quick video of the scene. &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.co/GMC5fxcg8h&quot;&gt;pic.twitter.com/GMC5fxcg8h&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&amp;mdash; Dylan Doppelt (@DylanDoppelt) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/DylanDoppelt/status/757369656617336832&quot;&gt;July 25, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The structure that fell was at the Illinois Medical District station on the Blue Line route. A train was reportedly at the station, but unaffected by the collapse. Service was suspended on sections of the Blue Line, as well as on the Brown and Red Lines, due to other storm-related damage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;inset external-content-inset&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot;&gt;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Part of The Pedestrian walkway at the Blue Line collapse during the storm near Rush No one hurt. &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/WGNNews&quot;&gt;@WGNNews&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.co/nIZSHA8EMR&quot;&gt;pic.twitter.com/nIZSHA8EMR&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&amp;mdash; Erik Runge (@WGNErik) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/WGNErik/status/757377435293749248&quot;&gt;July 25, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Chicago Fire Department said the collapse was weather-related, and that crews had been called to the station after a lightning strike.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chaos reigned Sunday ahead of the Democratic National Convention, as the party&amp;rsquo;s head was forced to quit, thousands of protesters took to the streets and delegates threatened a walk-out over Hillary Clinton&amp;rsquo;s vice-presidential pick.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On the eve of the four-day convention to nominate the county&amp;rsquo;s first female presidential candidate, Democratic National Committee Chairwoman Debbie Wasserman Schultz resigned in disgrace over the hack of emails that showed DNC staffers favoring Clinton over her then rival, Vermont Sen. Bernie Sanders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/dnc-chairwoman-quits-after-anti-sanders-emails-leaked-2016-07-24&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;DNC chairwoman quits over leaned anti-Sanders emails&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Meanwhile, throngs of Sanders supporters marched and pounded on drums, chanting &amp;ldquo;Hell no, DNC &amp;mdash; we won&amp;rsquo;t vote for Hillary&amp;rdquo; in the sweltering heat during the first in an expected series of protests in Philadelphia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A leading Sanders supporter, Norman Solomon, also said a &amp;ldquo;vast majority&amp;rdquo; of the socialist&amp;rsquo;s delegates were considering turning their backs &amp;mdash; or even walking out of the Wells Fargo Center &amp;mdash; during Virginia Sen. Tim Kaine&amp;rsquo;s acceptance speech to run as Clinton&amp;rsquo;s second-in-command.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Also read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-things-to-know-about-tim-kaine-2016-07-22&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;5 things to know about Tim Kaine&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The ouster of Wasserman Schultz, a Florida congresswoman, came just hours after Democrats revealed that she had been replaced as their convention&amp;rsquo;s chairwoman by little-known Rep. Marcia Fudge (D-Ohio).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But in a statement announcing she was stepping down as DNC chair effective &amp;ldquo;at the end of this convention&amp;rdquo; Wasserman Schultz insisted she would still open and close the convention.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A Democratic source said it would be &amp;ldquo;very unusual&amp;rdquo; for anyone other than the convention chair to gavel the political gathering into session.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wasserman Schultz also said she planned to &amp;ldquo;address our delegates about the stakes involved in this election not only for Democrats, but for all Americans.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That claim raised the specter of her getting booed off the stage &amp;mdash; like Texas Sen. Ted Cruz was last week when he refused to endorse Republican candidate Donald Trump at the GOP convention in Cleveland.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/unity-may-be-elusive-as-democratic-convention-starts-2016-07-24&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Unity may be elusive as Democratic convention starts&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;There&amp;rsquo;s no way a speech by Debbie Wasserman Schultz will be well-received by Bernie Sanders delegates,&amp;rdquo; Solomon, national coordinator of the Bernie Delegates Network, told The Post.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He called Wasserman Schultz&amp;rsquo;s resignation &amp;ldquo;long overdue.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;She should have resigned many months ago. Now the question looms over us here in Philadelphia: Why not immediately? Why wait till the end of the week?&amp;rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;University of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato said that &amp;ldquo;unless the Clinton campaign has an agreement with the Sanders bunch to let her leave gracefully, it could be a mistake&amp;rdquo; to let Wasserman Schultz take the podium.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Of course she&amp;rsquo;ll be booed, absent an agreement,&amp;rdquo; Sabato said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A Democratic insider and Clinton backer with knowledge of the talks that led to the ouster said party officials were working furiously to keep her from making a speech.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Debbie wouldn&amp;rsquo;t go,&amp;rdquo; the source said. &amp;ldquo;She wouldn&amp;rsquo;t do it gracefully. She didn&amp;rsquo;t do it nicely.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It won&amp;rsquo;t be anything like Cruz, though. He was the runner-up for the nomination, and that mattered.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The national audience has no clue who [Wasserman Schultz] is, and she&amp;rsquo;s resigning.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On Twitter, Trump gloated over the disarray, writing: &amp;ldquo;I always said that Debbie Wasserman Schultz was overrated. The Dems Convention is cracking up and Bernie is exhausted, no energy left!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;inset external-content-inset&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot;&gt;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;I always said that Debbie Wasserman Schultz was overrated. The Dems Convention is cracking up and Bernie is exhausted, no energy left!&lt;/p&gt;
&amp;mdash; Donald J. Trump (@realDonaldTrump) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/757311921095925760&quot;&gt;July 24, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He also heaped praise on Wasserman Schultz&amp;rsquo;s GOP counterpart, tweeting: &amp;ldquo;Today proves what I have always known, that @Reince Priebus is the tough one and the smart one, not Debbie Wasserman Shultz (sic).&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;inset external-content-inset&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot;&gt;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Today proves what I have always known, that &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/Reince&quot;&gt;@Reince&lt;/a&gt; Priebus is the tough one and the smart one, not Debbie Wasserman Shultz (&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/DWStweets&quot;&gt;@DWStweets&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt;
&amp;mdash; Donald J. Trump (@realDonaldTrump) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/757309616254545920&quot;&gt;July 24, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Meanwhile, Democratic sources told CNN that the hacked emails had inflamed Sanders supporters and could destroy the party-unity deal between Sanders and Clinton, with one Democrat saying: &amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s gas meets flame.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And Clinton aides floated a conspiracy theory that Russian hackers had engineered the email scandal in a bid to help elect Trump, who has predicted he&amp;rsquo;d &amp;ldquo;get along very well&amp;rdquo; with Russian President Vladimir Putin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Clinton campaign manager Robby Mook noted that WikiLeaks released the nearly 20,000 emails right after &amp;ldquo;changes to the Republican platform to make it more pro-Russian.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I don&amp;rsquo;t think it&amp;rsquo;s coincidental that these emails were released on the eve of our convention here, and I think that&amp;rsquo;s disturbing,&amp;rdquo; Mook told CNN&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;State of the Union.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sen. Charles Schumer (D-NY) also said the hack raised &amp;ldquo;a lot of suspicious and worrisome questions.&amp;rdquo; Sanders called the emails &amp;ldquo;outrageous, but not a great shock,&amp;rdquo; telling CNN that he&amp;rsquo;d long accused the DNC of trying to undermine him in favor of Clinton.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Are the Russians trying to influence our election? I don&amp;rsquo;t have proof of that, but we should be looking into it,&amp;rdquo; Schumer said during his weekly Sunday news conference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In a statement, he later said Wasserman Schultz &amp;ldquo;made the right decision&amp;rdquo; to quit, adding: &amp;ldquo;While she deserves thanks for her years of service, the party now needs new leadership that will open the doors of the party and welcome in working people and young people.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wasserman Schultz will be replaced as interim party chair by Donna Brazile, an ardent Hillary Clinton supporter who on Sunday said she had apologized to the Sanders campaign over the hacked emails.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I think, the allegations, the emails, the insensitivity, the stupidity needs to be addressed, and we are going the address it,&amp;rdquo; Brazile told ABC&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;This Week.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;She is taking a leave from her role as a CNN analyst.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A longtime Democrat strategist, Brazile ran Vice President Al Gore&amp;rsquo;s disastrous 2000 presidential campaign &amp;mdash; which saw him start wearing &amp;ldquo;reassuring,&amp;rdquo; earth-toned clothing in a failed bid to win over voters before losing to George W. Bush in an election decided by the US Supreme Court.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nypost.com/2016/07/24/convention-chaos-already-dnc-chair-out-protesters-storm-philly/&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;This report originally appeared on NYPost.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;article-image-wrap shareable&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;article-image MG&quot; src=&quot;http://localhost/marketmasterclass/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ei.marketwatch.comMultimedia20141020PhotosMGMW-CW922_moneyo_20141020130945_MG-1b2a76920d836970c8fb2299b5accab2181e62a5.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;cite&gt;Terrence Horan/MarketWatch&lt;/cite&gt; 

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dear Moneyologist,&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would like to know your advice about how adult children can protect themselves from the financial obligations of their parents.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My brother and I were raised in poverty and my mother still lives beneath the poverty line with government assistance covering some of her expenses. She has many medical issues and does not work. She is approaching 70 years of age.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My brother has a wife and two children and lives in another state. I am married with no children and live a few miles from my mother. We both have decent jobs and are what I would consider middle-class suburbanites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our relationship with my mother has been strained for many years. There is not a lot of contact between my brother and our mother, or expectation of assistance emotionally or financially. It has been this way for many years. There are no hard feelings on this front. My relationship with my brother is strong.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have assisted my mom financially since I started working as a teenager. About 10 years ago, I got married and bought a house, had a very demanding job plus responsibility for my mother&amp;rsquo;s medical, financial and emotional well-being. When I had medical issues of my own, it was all too much to handle and I landed in therapy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/i-secretly-charge-an-hourly-rate-for-caring-for-my-mom-2015-02-06&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;I (secretly) charge an hourly rate for caring for my mom&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While I still care for and provide for my mother, I learned the co-dependent relationship I had with her was unhealthy and I have scaled back significantly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I pay for her to have high-speed internet service at her home. I activated the service to be able to work from her house during a stretch of major medical issues where she needed someone to be with her. She now has a home health aide (government provided) three days a week and I have not found myself in that situation in over a year, but I still consider the Wi-Fi insurance, so I keep it. I also include her on my family cellphone plan. I bring her household items and groceries on every visit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;shareable&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I no longer pay for any more of her debt. She uses her money on things I would consider careless and frivolous, but it is her money and I no longer intervene or express my frustration.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;&lt;cite&gt;Cindy in N.Y.&lt;/cite&gt;

&lt;/footer&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I no longer pay for any more of her debt. She uses her money on things I would consider careless and frivolous, but it is her money and I no longer intervene or express my frustration. She finds herself in a bind on occasion, having things like her cable TV or her land line phone terminated.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;She frequently gets calls and letters from collection agencies. These were things she would bring to my attention in the past and I would pay past-due balances, late fees and reconnection fees &amp;mdash; regularly. I no longer offer to do that. Over the years she has gotten the message and she really doesn&amp;rsquo;t push them on me anymore. It has relieved a lot of stress from my relationship with her. However, now they are just ignored and pile up without any action.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today, it is very important to me to focus on my well-being, which means not returning to our previous relationship which left me damaged financially and emotionally. At the same time I have a lot of stress and anxiety about where this will leave me if and when (a) she passes on, (b) a decision has to be made to change her living situation (in my home or a nursing home) or (c) something major happens, like a legal judgment against her.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My husband is financially smart. Without him, I would have likely traveled down the same financial road as my mother. With him, I have had the guidance and support to pay off years of mounting debt, buy a house and start saving for retirement. The thought of taking a hit to everything we have worked so hard to build causes a lot of stress. My husband has concerns about me not acquiring her debt and/or expenses when the time comes and he feels it will destroy us financially. I don&amp;rsquo;t disagree with him. I just struggle with doing right by everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don&amp;rsquo;t know what I would be responsible for financially as her daughter when she is truly incapable. I&amp;rsquo;m not sure if it&amp;rsquo;s smarter to move her in with us or start to look into assisted living/nursing homes, especially if covered by the government programs that have covered her all these years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What could I be doing prepare or protect myself financially?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cindy in N.Y.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dear Cindy,&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Rarely has a letter moved me as much as yours. You have created a wonderful life for yourself and done so without becoming hard of heart to those in your life or bitter about the past. You have maintained a strong relationship with your brother and a relationship with your mother that is based on love and service, while maintaining healthy emotional and financial boundaries. You have since learned that you can&amp;rsquo;t do everything, nor should you have to do everything.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m glad that you finally realized that you cannot live her life for her. You deserve a happy life, one where you are free to enjoy the small moments and look forward to a secure future. That&amp;rsquo;s nothing to feel guilty about. Plenty of children would have walked away. You didn&amp;rsquo;t. This is something that your mother was either unable or unwilling to provide for you. In the face of remarkable odds, you provided it for yourself. And yet you are still thinking of others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;shareable&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You deserve a happy life, one where you are free to enjoy the small moments and look forward to a secure future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;&lt;cite&gt;The Moneyologist&lt;/cite&gt;

&lt;/footer&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Moving your mom in with you seems to run counter to your desire to maintain healthy boundaries,&amp;rdquo; says Anne Tumlinson, founder of Daughterhood, a Washington, DC-based organization that provides information and resources to people caring for aging parents. &amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s not necessary in New York. Additionally, your mother is already obviously on Medicaid so you don&amp;rsquo;t need to worry about whether your mother will qualify, which is usually a huge thing given people&amp;rsquo;s assets and incomes that usually need to be spent-down first.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are not alone. An estimated 43.5 million adults in the U.S. have provided unpaid care to an adult or a child within the prior 12 months, according to the 2015 report &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/my-mother-lives-below-the-poverty-line-but-i-stopped-paying-her-debts-2016-07-09?siteid=rss&amp;amp;rss=1&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;Caregiving in the U.S.&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo; by the AARP Public Policy Institute, the advocacy group for Americans aged 50 years and older. More than 18% of the respondents interviewed reported being caregivers. The majority of caregivers are female (60%), the AARP said, and the average caregiver is 49 years of age.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Listen:&lt;/strong&gt; Catey Hill and Quentin Fottrell&amp;rsquo;s podcast &lt;a href=&quot;https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/marketwatch-money-markets/id157123762?mt=2&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;Money, Markets &amp;amp; More&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/apple.co/1STkdE7&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;(on iTunes): &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-middle-income-earners-can-own-a-big-city-home-2016-07-07&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Buy a condo in San Francisco for $168,000&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://on.wsj.com/1USVPli&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;and &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/gift-giving-etiquette-when-to-speak-up-2016-07-08-121073853&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;When the best man forgets to bring a wedding gift.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s highly unlikely that you would be held responsible for your mother&amp;rsquo;s debts when she passes on. Don&amp;rsquo;t co-sign any loans and maintain a clear line between her finances and your own and keep an eye on your credit score, in the unlikely event that your mother would take out a loan in your name (especially if you shared the same first name). &amp;ldquo;Unless you are a co-signer on a debt, you are in no way liable for your mother&amp;rsquo;s debts,&amp;rdquo; says Blake Harris, an attorney at Mile High Estate Planning in Denver. &amp;ldquo;There isn&amp;rsquo;t anything you need to do aside from continuing to follow your husband&amp;rsquo;s wise financial advice.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Some 28 U.S. states have so-called filial responsibility laws, which can be traced back to colonial times and (in theory) impose a duty on adult children to support their impoverished parents. Those states don&amp;rsquo;t include New York. &lt;a href=&quot;http://rosenblattesq.com/lawyer/2013/05/25/Estate-Planning/Filial-Responsibility-Laws_bl6821.htm&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s a list&lt;/a&gt; of the other 28 that do have those laws, even if they don&amp;rsquo;t practice them. One of those states is Pennsylvania, which did use filial responsibility to force an adult child to pay his mother&amp;rsquo;s bill. In 2012, Pennsylvania court ruled that John Pittas must pay his mother&amp;rsquo;s $93,000 nursing home bill after she moved to Greece. Otherwise, they are rarely enforced.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The AARP and other organizations have &lt;a href=&quot;http://assets.aarp.org/www.aarp.org_/articles/foundation/aa66r2_care.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;helpful guides&lt;/a&gt; for preparing to care for an elderly parent. This includes figuring out what your mother&amp;rsquo;s needs might be and forming a team (that includes your brother and husband). There are &lt;a href=&quot;http://assets.aarp.org/www.aarp.org_/articles/foundation/aa66r2_care.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;many online resources&lt;/a&gt; to see if she qualifies for public benefits of state, federal, and private programs that help pay for groceries, prescription drugs, health insurance and home help. The best time to think about these issues is now, before there&amp;rsquo;s a crisis. And, as my former colleague &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/caring-for-mom-and-dad-take-care-of-yourself-too-2014-07-03&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Elizabeth O&amp;rsquo;Brien wrote&lt;/a&gt;, take care of yourself too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from the Moneyologist&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;article-image-wrap shareable&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;article-image MG&quot; src=&quot;http://localhost/marketmasterclass/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ei.marketwatch.comMultimedia20141020PhotosMGMW-CW922_moneyo_20141020130945_MG-1b2a76920d836970c8fb2299b5accab2181e62a5-1.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;cite&gt;Terrence Horan/MarketWatch&lt;/cite&gt; 

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dear Moneyologist,&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I mailed my 21-year-old nephew a birthday card and check for $50. He received the card before his birthday, opened it and cashed the check with no acknowledgment of receipt. I know this because the check cleared the bank two days before his birthday. I&amp;rsquo;m not so old fashioned or naive to expect a handwritten thank you but he can&amp;rsquo;t even send a text? Is it unreasonable to expect acknowledgment before running to the bank? Where have all the manners gone?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Baffled Uncle&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dear Baffled,&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Peter, Paul and Mary (&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZgXNVA9ngx8&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;almost&lt;/a&gt;) asked the same question.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It takes a lot to buy a card, sign it, find the correct address and put a stamp on the envelope. I&amp;rsquo;m not kidding. Maybe it&amp;rsquo;s my age, but sending someone anything by snail mail is an ordeal. I visit the nearest shop that sells stamps at least once a week to buy a stamp (as they often run out). It&amp;rsquo;s either that or stand in line at the post office, staring at the guy with six packages and questions about the weight and category for each one. I could sign up to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.stamps.com/&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;Stamps.com&lt;/a&gt; and avoid all of that. When it comes to thanking a friend or relative for a check, however, you should always make that trip.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;article-image-wrap shareable&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;article-image MG&quot; src=&quot;http://localhost/marketmasterclass/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ei.marketwatch.comMultimedia20160720PhotosMGMW-ES037_money__20160720130712_MG-097657eb543dc9aa120275b867c3c8f39da0054f.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;cite&gt;Terrence Horan/MarketWatch&lt;/cite&gt; 

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most Americans believe good manners in the U.S. are on the decline over the last several decades, according to a &lt;a href=&quot;http://bit.ly/29TSLDe&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;recent survey&lt;/a&gt; of 1,000 adults by the Associated Press and NORC, a research organization affiliated with the University of Chicago. Some 74% of respondents bemoaned the prevalence of the usual suspects like cell phone use, increasingly course political discourse, tasteless jokes and bad language, but they also found a difference between younger and older generations. Almost half of Americans aged 18 to 29 feel it is acceptable to use cell phones in restaurants, for instance, while only 22% of those over age 60 agree. This is no excuse but, chances are, your nephew has never had to post a letter in his life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;shareable&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have a phrase in Ireland: &amp;ldquo;He didn&amp;rsquo;t lick it off the stones.&amp;rdquo; It means that people&amp;rsquo;s bad behavior is either inherited or taught to them by their elders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;&lt;cite&gt;The Moneyologist&lt;/cite&gt;

&lt;/footer&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Indeed, sales of traditional greeting cards have fallen by nearly 30% in dollar terms over the last decade when adjusted for inflation &amp;mdash; to $6.1 billion in 2014 and are expected to fall to $4.3 billion in 2018, according to industry research firm IbisWorld. Why send a card when you can send a funny GIF on Facebook? Even Hallmark has a $1 per month e-card subscription service. A wedding anniversary, Mother&amp;rsquo;s Day, Bar Mitzvah, partner&amp;rsquo;s birthday &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/why-facebook-wont-kill-the-greeting-card-2013-04-15&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;all require a card&lt;/a&gt;. (If a friend announces that his grandparent died on Facebook, you don&amp;rsquo;t want to press the &amp;ldquo;like&amp;rdquo; button.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Don&amp;rsquo;t miss: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/my-best-man-didnt-even-give-me-a-gift-after-our-wedding-2016-07-06&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Should I tell the best man he should have given me a wedding gift?&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And so to your nephew&amp;rsquo;s lack of appreciation. He&amp;rsquo;s 21 years old. Sure, he&amp;rsquo;s no longer a child. But I am going to give your nephew and his parents 50% share of the blame. Or give them both 100% of the blame. Either way, they&amp;rsquo;re both on the hook here. We have a phrase in Ireland (Yes, I&amp;rsquo;m going there again): &amp;ldquo;He didn&amp;rsquo;t lick it off the stones.&amp;rdquo; It means that people&amp;rsquo;s bad behavior is either inherited or taught to them by their elders. Your nephew proves himself very capable of cashing a check, but not licking a stamp. Regardless, he too should know better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So what do you do? Even if you are not his godfather, I suggest stepping into that role. If you&amp;rsquo;re close enough to give him a check, you&amp;rsquo;re close enough to call up his parents or email them and say, &amp;ldquo;Did Kevin get my card? I want to make sure as there was a check in it.&amp;rdquo; Or speak to him directly and say the same thing. Does it tarnish the goodwill of the birthday card and check? It does a bit. But there is an opportunity here to give your nephew (and his parents) a more valuable lesson: The family&amp;rsquo;s reputation is on the line here, as well as next year&amp;rsquo;s check.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Do you have questions about inheritance, tipping, weddings, family feuds, friends or any tricky issues relating to manners and money? Send them to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/qfottrell@marketwatch.com&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;MarketWatch&amp;rsquo;s Moneyologist&lt;/a&gt; and please include the state where you live (no full names will be used).&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Would you like to sign up to an email alert when a new Moneyologist column has been published? If so, click on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/tools/alerts/newsColumn.asp&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;this link.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from the Moneyologist&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PHILADELPHIA &amp;mdash; Democrats gathering for their national convention began the process of unifying the party around Hillary Clinton by prompting the resignation of a top party official viewed with bitter suspicion by primary runner-up Bernie Sanders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The resignation of Debbie Wasserman Schultz as chairwoman of the Democratic National Committee came after the disclosure of a trove of hacked emails showing DNC officials working to undermine Sanders&amp;rsquo;s campaign.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/dnc-chairwoman-quits-after-anti-sanders-emails-leaked-2016-07-24&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;DNC chairwoman quits after anti-Sanders emails leaked&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After hours of private talks, Wasserman Schultz, a congresswoman from Florida, said she would step down after the convention ends &amp;mdash; meaning she would still have to face pro-Sanders delegates when she takes on the traditional role of gaveling the opening and closing of the event. She will also speak at the convention.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Her departure removes what was becoming a major distraction on the eve of the Democratic National Convention, a four-day event aimed chiefly at re-introducing Clinton to a general-election audience, hoping a telling of her life story and motivations will draw in voters who don&amp;rsquo;t like the alternative, Republican Donald Trump.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After Republicans gathered in Cleveland last week used criticism of Clinton to rally their troops, Philadelphia also will feature a heavy dose of Trump attacks, officials said. But Democrats said their more urgent task is to pump up Clinton and tell voters her story and motivations. She will be formally nominated as the first woman to lead a major party ticket on Tuesday, and accept with a prime-time speech Thursday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The party also will seek to showcase her broad appeal with an endorsement from former New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg, an independent and former Republican who considered a presidential run of his own this year. He will speak&amp;nbsp;on Wednesday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/on-eve-of-democratic-convention-party-seeks-unity-with-officials-ouster-1469403856&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Donald Trump said Sunday that his proposal to suspend immigration from countries &amp;ldquo;compromised by terrorism&amp;rdquo; is actually an expansion of his plan to ban foreign Muslims from entering the U.S.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The GOP nominee didn&amp;rsquo;t mention the Muslim ban during his acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention speech on Thursday, instead saying that immigration from countries undermined by terrorism.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Asked if the change in phrasing meant he&amp;rsquo;d stepped back from the plan, Trump told NBC&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Meet the Press&amp;rdquo; it was just the opposite.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I actually don&amp;rsquo;t think it&amp;rsquo;s a rollback,&amp;rdquo; Trump said in the interview that aired Sunday. &amp;ldquo;In fact, you could say it&amp;rsquo;s an expansion. I&amp;rsquo;m looking now at territory. People were so upset when I used the word Muslim. Oh, you can&amp;rsquo;t use the word Muslim. Remember this. And I&amp;rsquo;m okay with that, because I&amp;rsquo;m talking territory instead of Muslim.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Trump admitted his new stance could now affect allies like France, rocked by ISIS terror attacks in Nice and Paris.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s their own fault, because they&amp;rsquo;ve allowed people over years to come into their territory,&amp;rdquo; Trump said. &amp;ldquo;And that&amp;rsquo;s why Brexit happened, okay? Because the U.K. is saying, &amp;ldquo;We&amp;rsquo;re tired of this stuff, what&amp;rsquo;s going on, we&amp;rsquo;re tired of.&amp;rsquo;&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Trump did not say which countries could be affected under the plan, but promised &amp;ldquo;extreme vetting.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;We&amp;rsquo;re going to have tough standards,&amp;rdquo; he said. &amp;ldquo;And if a person can&amp;rsquo;t prove &amp;hellip; that they&amp;rsquo;re from an area, and if a person can&amp;rsquo;t prove what they have to be able to prove, they&amp;rsquo;re not coming into this country. And I would stop the Syrian migration and a Syrian from coming into this country in two seconds.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It appeared that Trump had backed off his December Muslim ban plan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Last month, the tycoon announced that as president he would &amp;ldquo;suspend immigration from areas of the world when there is a proven history of terrorism against the United States, Europe, or our allies.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In a separate interview airing Sunday night, Trump said he saved rival Ted Cruz from more political humiliation by entering the convention area Wednesday night as the Texas senator was getting booed for his non-endorsement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;In retrospect, I wish I would have waited another minute. Because he was being booed right off the stage,&amp;rdquo; Trump said in a separate interview to air Sunday night on Showtime&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;The Circus.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I walked in and the arena went crazy. Because there&amp;rsquo;s great unity in the Republican Party, and people don&amp;rsquo;t know it. Had I not walked in, I think that audience would have ripped him off the stage. I think I did him a big favor.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Trump plans to fund super-PACs aimed at ending the political careers of Cruz and Ohio Gov. John Kasich, who shunned Trump&amp;rsquo;s convention in his home state.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cruz&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;life in politics may be over because people are so angry with him,&amp;rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://nypost.com/2016/07/24/trump-calls-immigration-plan-expansion-of-muslim-ban/&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;This report originally appeared in NYPost.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PHILADELPHIA &amp;mdash; Donald Trump will try to steal some of Hillary Clinton&amp;rsquo;s thunder during the Democratic National Convention here this week with a slate of swing-state appearances that will test the appeal of his new running mate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Indiana Gov. Mike Pence will join the GOP presidential nominee at stops in Virginia and North Carolina on Monday, Florida on Tuesday and Pennsylvania on Wednesday, according to a campaign schedule. Other GOP allies will hover around Philadelphia for counterprogramming during the Democratic gathering.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Republican nominees in their travels will jointly appear at two town hall meetings, a rally, a national veterans&amp;rsquo; convention and what the campaign described as a Hispanic leadership round table.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The two men will then split up on the campaign trail&amp;nbsp;as Clinton takes the Philadelphia stage&amp;nbsp;Thursday, aides to the New York businessman said. Pence will campaign with his wife, Karen.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Clinton last week eschewed the tradition of letting the opposing party have the national stage&amp;nbsp;during its convention, and&amp;nbsp;campaigned in Ohio&amp;nbsp;while the Republican gathering took place there. Clinton&amp;nbsp;surrogates also traveled to Cleveland to push back against the frequent attacks on Clinton at the GOP event.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-aims-to-rain-on-hillary-clintons-parade-1469405954&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More from MarketWatch&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BERLIN &amp;mdash; A man apparently set off a bomb in the German town of Ansbach on Sunday evening, killing himself and injuring at least 10 people, police said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The blast occurred shortly after 10 p.m. outside the entrance to an open-air concert attended by 2,000 people, Ansbach Mayor Carda Seidel said at a press conference.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.marketwatch.com/story/asylum-seeker-arrested-in-deadly-machete-attack-in-germany-2016-07-24&quot; class=&quot;icon none&quot;&gt;Asylum-seeker arrested in deadly machete attack in Germany&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The people inside the concert venue were safely evacuated, she said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It was apparently an explosive device,&amp;rdquo; Seidel said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The man who died was believed to be the person who caused the explosion, police said.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ansbach officials said none of the injuries were believed to be life-threatening.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wsj.com/articles/one-dead-several-injured-by-explosion-in-germany-1469403515&quot; target=&quot;_new&quot; class=&quot;icon&quot;&gt;An expanded version of this report appears on WSJ.com.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
